The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classics cheaper.
Maybe she won't be long.
We have written on Mobile.cz many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
In addition, the CTU also confirmed that the SMS price is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming charges regulation, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks competition that would really want to start a fight.
It may sound paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and a penetration of over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, are happy to say that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this he often also called for the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (CTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has expressed several times that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classic operator with his own network probably does not have much chance (after all, it would be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is one more option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought significant reductions in prices, to which classical operators had to respond.
At the same time, in the UK, there were voices like ours before Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the start of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
At the same time, the financial group Penta is behind Mobilking, which owns, among other things, U:phone in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move as well as a bet on an unburdened target group.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Administrative men elect a mobile operator that they like and trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could be found in Poland as well.
Vodafon's press agent Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of services."
In the Czech Republic no chance, they call mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobileking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic, negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, the press spokesperson of the financial group Penta in a telephone interview.
It has indirectly confirmed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not in favour of this idea.
Rather, on the contrary, they are trying to do everything in their power not to create any potential competitors.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been secreted for a long time by the GTS Novera group, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of O2 Telephony in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner the better.
We discussed this possibility repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to advance with some of them in the negotiations," says the spokesperson of the Group, Pavel Kaidl.
Well, maybe it's for a better time.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be looking forward to perhaps by the end of the year.
For the time being, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is a space on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of the Telephonics O2.
Other operators also appeal to the specificity of the Czech market.
The T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in rare harmony with O2: "For the time being, we have not recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to build further."
And he adds: "It's hard for some virtual operator to show up on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a specific agreement on the table to be considered in this short term."
Vodafone holds its attention to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says, "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider the most profitable in terms of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile Internet."
Responsible offices - with operators one hand
Mobile operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would increase competition, lead to a drop in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
Why, then, make it easier for such a competitor to enter?
The fact that when it comes to doing something, they can pull a rope, even the U:phone pulls.
Probably the biggest pressure towards the CTU went at the time of the creation of U:phone by T-Mobile.
This is testified to public information from the CTU website.
But now the U:phone fits as an argument as to why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would impose high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, it is a direct concern of the Czech regulatory authorities.
This is not just about the position of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other advanced countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stand on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator on the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential candidates was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," said Kristian Chalupa of the Department of External Relations.
The representatives of the operators do not seem to be surprised at the expression thus formulated.
It is more than a serious one from an office to represent consumers' interests and, inter alia, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the drop in prices are clearly not among the interests of the OHS.
In fact, it is shocking for the entire case to have the impression of three mobile operators reacting.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is offered all by itself.
As well as the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is certainly only a work of chance and a tough competition.
"The Office has not found signs of anti-competitive action in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, so it is not adequately responsible for its conduct on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to be missing the telecommunications regulator," he said.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by the CTU, according to which telecommunications is a single market from a competitive point of view.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - you always need the consent of the network operator to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - he has quite logically - on his network monopoly.
So in a particular segment, it has to be dominant.
However, even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning for the UOHS that the three mobile operators are doing the same.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
The delegation of responsibility for the CTU is a fairly common trick in telecoms, which gives the UOHS hands away from the whole matter.
We've met him in a few similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act with the extension of the competence of the CTU to competition in telecommunications, it was not possible to enforce, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
This must be known by the representatives of the UOHS more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It works when no one's watching
At the same time, the operation of some pseudovirtual operators, which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies issuing their own mobile phone service prices, but they are only partially public.
It is usually a company dealing with multilevel marketing.
It has its own mobile phone service, such as Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these companies usually only get to the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company acts as a classic corporate customer vis-à-vis the operator, ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer then gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators are prohibited.
"If there are cases you are talking about, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," she replied to our question on this issue by Martina Kemrová.
However, it is unlikely that a similar activity to those of responsible mobile operators could not be brought forward.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, it may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are opposed to such a procedure.
The activities of these companies have negligible profits and, unlike the real virtual operators, do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, but the services of these companies use only a negligible percentage of customers.
Moreover, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not kept in their name, so they cannot have it fully as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that's what should be weird at least.
In addition, another question for the UNHS is being opened.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It is necessary to say that the UOHS has a relatively strong authority to reveal a similar activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the operator’s explanation that they have no idea about it and their business conditions prohibit it.
When We Will Not Be the Dearest
As has been done several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a noticeable decline in service prices.
In so doing, in virtually all the countries where virtual operators were created, classic operators tried to defend their creation more or less.
Jimi arguments used were practically identical - too small, or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In advanced countries, however, it was precisely in these moments that regulatory authorities hit, which defended not the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or by informal pressure, the first virtual operator was created and packed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities throw the whole case over as hot potatoes.
In our experience, we can't help but feel that they're more than welcome to be unclear about the competences in these cases.
But let's not throw the flute into the rye.
If background information is correct and the virtual operator appears here really soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain insensitive to reject (discrimination) other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling the storm than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four versions of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Czech State Day presented the new recordings of the state anthem where my home.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra led by Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, chorus presentation and instrumental version.
Kateřina Knežinková and Adam Plachetka took part in the song.
The authors of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
On iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymen.
He previously told the Czech Radio that he deliberately chose to sing solo versions of singers with young representative voices that are distinct and popular.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure both of them were well understood," he said.
The Czech State Anthem will celebrate the 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where my home first sounded in 1834 on the boards of the Stavov Theatre in the original Czech game Fidlováček Josef Kajetán Tyl, supplemented by music by František Škroup.
She got popular, and people spontaneously took her for their own.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first song became a natural part of the national anthem.
One of the seven national symbols remained after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
