Prague public transport will take you to the chip on Wednesday for the first time
Wednesday 1st October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date on which the first passengers will be boarded by metro, tram and bus, who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At this point, he can get about a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day coupon (this will apply from 1 January 2009) while also having their chip card recorded at the information centres and workplaces of the Transport Company in metro stations of the Museum, Bridge, Holešovice Railway Station, Angel, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Raj Garden, Kačerov and Luka.
Since yesterday, coupons can also be purchased via the Internet on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over 400 customers in the afternoon.
Those who start to use the Internet store can definitely forget the windows at the metro stations, where they had to stay regularly in long queues on paper tickets.
The coupon buys it online and on the Opencard card it is uploaded to one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
"In these places, passengers are at the disposal of a bulkhead with trained service, which will help those interested with online shopping and will also record their purchased coupon on their card," said the project spokesperson Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries it will be possible to load electronic coupons on the Opencard also in self-service slots, which are installed in several vestibules of the subway.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminding ticket markers, and passengers may have noticed them at metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltava.
"Now there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be 80," he added.
The ticket checks the driver's slot machine
The machine service that starts working tomorrow is simple.
Just insert the Opencard chip card into them and the previously paid coupon will be uploaded to it itself.
The electronic coupons from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
Thus, in suburban trains and bus lines with the number 300 to 499, which are driven mainly by the inhabitants of the towns of Central Bohemia.
"On the trains included in Prague Integrated Transport, the guides are equipped with card readers, using which they detect the time and frequency validity of coupons," said Filip Drápal from the Ropid organization, who prepares the timetables of Prague public transport.
The suburban buses have card readers built into the cash register at the driver's.
Therefore, not only does a chip card need to be shown to the driver, but it is also necessary to attach the Opencard to the designated location on the side of the cash register.
This will check the validity of recorded coupons.
"If a passenger needs to verify the validity of recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drapal added.
Passengers who do not take suburban buses and do not remember when their coupon ends can go back to self-service machines where card coupons are recorded.
Here the information about the validity of their documents is displayed on the display of the device.
Sudety wanted a U.S. referendum
In 1945, the Sudet Germans asked for the integration of Sumava into the United States.
It comes from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Research Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the auspices of the United States of America at least.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudetian Germans reportedly turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is based, among other things, on a letter that has been preserved in one private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Research Library.
The Germans from Český Krumlov are asking in a letter from the President of the United States not to allow the return of "Sumava County" - taken by Hitler on the basis of a Munich agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly, and we really want to be sure by the words that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says the letter, "People to whom the fate of Sumava lies."
Because the connection to Czechoslovakia is allegedly giving the Sudetian Germans - in the knowledge of the Czech national character - the hope of brutality, recklessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, begs the authors of the letter of the President of the United States to take over Šumavou by the protectorate for now and forever.
