When a rat or cockroach flees from danger, does that mean that they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have feelings.
But how could it be possible to verify that they feel the same way when they act like us?
For several years, the internet magazine "Edge" has published the contributions of well-known scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in his series presents the selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without you being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it when we can't even prove that consciousness has other people.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we begin to devote ourselves to another species and open the questions of perception or general awareness, we enter the insufferable terrain because the hardware does not match.
If a rat gets in danger, it will do the same thing as many other animals: it will pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
People act in a similar way, of which some scientists consider comparable subjective experiences.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal living.
This is because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its share of short-term memory and performance or control functions).
This vast area is much more developed in man than in other primates, and it seems that other creatures are completely lacking.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that a person differs even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could conceal the linguistic nature of a person: since so much of his perception is associated with the tongue, it is often said that consciousness depends on him.
In this case, we could rule out animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter in the language, the language would certainly affect it, so animal consciousness, however designed, would probably differ from most of our states of consciousness.
That's why it's hard to figure out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it cannot even measure itself, because of its special hardware, to analyse itself based on our own experience, it puts us in the face of great problems.
Most of my basics relate to the content of conscious experiences, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically easier to access.
It would be possible to examine processes in animal consciousness regardless of their content, and that is exactly what is happening in the short-term memory studies in primates, especially in the case of visualization.
But this approach, devoted to Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses more on neural corelates of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: they can both be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also underlines the importance of the unfrontal cortex for the implementation of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
It's from the fact that an emotional system like the fear system is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of a defense system located in the brain (or its consequences such as body reactions) uses operational memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely linked to those areas of cortex, which are characterized by primates, and especially humans.
In connection with linguistic nature, a fine gradation of perception arises, because using words and grammar, we can distinguish and categorize states so that we can assign them to others.
On the other hand, for example, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in cortex and brain strain areas, similar to Jaak Pankseep, which is more focused on the brain stem.
Because this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could participate in feelings perceived by multi-species.
I can't technically oppose it, but I think it's inconclusive.
Pankseep argues that what appears to us in rats and humans as fear is likely to feel the same way: How can it be verified, however, does Pankseep continue to say whether rats and humans feel the same way when they act alike?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the mere resemblance of behavior cannot prove the harmony of experience.
True, neural comparison moves us further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, on the other hand, cockroaches and brains.
But is the brain strain responsible for the feelings?
And even if it was possible to prove it with a human being, how would we like to prove it with rats?
I think that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and languages), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than emotional perception of rats.
Anyway, in this case, we can look forward to progress at the neural level if we measure the same with rats and humans.
As with rats, I don't explore language and consciousness, I don't explore feelings, I don't know if they exist.
