Proudness and Obstacles of Black People's Life in a Separate City
Hidden among the vast amusement parks of the larger Orlando, a few miles away from all the shiny, noisy and huge, lies a quiet city in which the pride and the difficulty of African-American life is revived.
Eatonville, the first completely black city that was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as easy as it was described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courses, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough quay, two schools and no prison."
Now it's a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Zora Festival to pay their respects to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains aside, although she made it a stop for tourists by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in the year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on races, many of the people here remain cautious of the views of strangers.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told," says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black growth and a community of almost 2400 people, where the rate of poverty is doubled compared to the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also of oak, a shielded example of the southern country's black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that was created by American slavery.
It is not surprising that the inhabitants here are both proud and protective.
And the concern about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way that Hurston is called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt books full of wails like "Mules and Men (Muly and Men)" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida Tourist Guide changed the town a short way to road 17, which leads through the often passed centre of Florida, on stage black history and human drama.
With the rank of a big drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced her reader to the store of the first Eatonville mayor Joe Clark, and then she turned to more private places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "there's a white brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the new husband of the widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sales drinks of all kinds and anything that fits into the hourly hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston Eatonville has connected itself to the government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
This clearly wasn't a typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it wasn't a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls' choir, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she said.
She still remembers Hurston as a fluffy eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time when she crashed into town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in the city, which is also proud of decent clothes today.
Most of the people were fascinated, said Franklin, but many were grinning.
"The people of Zoru have always loved to see," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, the present of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived before.
In Eatonville, there were no major funeral rituals or big public readings.
"I think neither her meaning for the world nor her legacy was understood at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's resume "Wraped in Rainbows (packed in rainbows)" published in 2003.
The change came in the 1980s.
The representatives of Orange County wanted to stretch a five-speed highway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is a local two-way route.
The spread of Orlando has already pushed interstate highway 4 across the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still getting out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950 ’ s, the struggle for mixing the races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and things at people who sat on the side," Franklin said.
"We actually had a lady here who killed it.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In a letter from The Orlando Sentinel of 1955, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's request for forced integration and his decision in the Brown case against the Education Chamber, saying that it was "for my race insulting rather than celebrating."
Residents now claim that school desegregation, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
"Black kids were used to being hugged - I remember - you hugged your teacher this morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N.Y. Natiri, Elly Dinkins' daughter and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This took time until teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You're not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there's a cultural barrier," said Miss Nathiri.
However, civil rights helped create space for many more Zory Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudices with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as "How someone can deny the pleasures of my presence!
I won't understand."
In 1975 Alice Walker arrived at Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, a praised résumé of Hurston from Robert E. Hemenway, who re-listed her in an American canon, came to the shelves in the bookstores.
The project with the highway arrived just as the most famous daughter of Eatonville found the lights of the ramp again.
The former Hurston neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen to her freeway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and each January many return to the celebration.
A few years later, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"The five highway streams have resurrected, you'd say it's just blown up, real civil pride," said Nathiri.
Boyd simply said, "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the motorway project helped to change the city's image.
Extra-urban like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the local church in 1993, began to appear in more numbers, and the people began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new one-storey library (named, of course, after Hurston) was opened in 2006 for the re-asphalled and beautiful Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: only six miles from the center of Orlando can sometimes act as a setting-up alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1980s.
(Today is 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come to search for a story and the meaning of Eatonville are still being treated cautiously.
The permission for most interviews must be given in advance and certain things - like wall paintings in the oldest Eatonville church painted by white people and depicting black people in the fields - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a courageous, confident teacher who likes to be full of red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
Even as the Hurston festival expanded, domestic pride also increased.
Especially young people want to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse and as proud, creative, industrious, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnics.
From Franklin's nephew's voice, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, there's an honest love for the village when he's planning to return to Eatonville after college to work in a local government or a police department that he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11-year-old twins from the Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenonova, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just pass through here, think, 'Well, this town is nothing against the others,' said Alondra Kenon recently on Sunday after church.
"But if you really stop and look for a moment into history, it's a very nice city."
