Interview - Blood that is again certain
Héma-Québec celebrated his tenth anniversary yesterday and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was justly pleased because Héma-Québec became one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after a scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Canadian Government launched a public inquiry, headed by Judge Horace Krever, in order to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to make recommendations not to repeat such a disaster.
While Judge Krever hesitated to submit his report, some provinces put in place a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
The Gélinea Committee held this role in Quebec.
After Gélineau and Krever's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, who was to be run by Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply all the provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Quebec started his activities in 1998, only 38% of the people still had confidence in the Québek blood system," recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
With constant efforts to increase the safety of blood products and the continued work in this area over the following years, we have regained public confidence," she says, proudly adds, by the beginning of 2008, Héma-Québek trusted almost 94% of the Québek population.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998 Héma-Quebec has applied the principle of prudence.
"At that time, in Europe, we witnessed the occurrence of many human cases of mad cow disease, new variants of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says the woman who has led the society since its establishment in 1998.
"And we had no idea whether this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of Krever and Gélineau's report that, in the event that we do not know this and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterised by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, it is necessary to take excitable measures.
In April 1999, therefore, we rejected blood from people who have abstained in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely demonstrated that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the principle of prudence made sense."
In 1999, a much more precise technique appeared on the market for the detection of HIV: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the presence of the virus itself in donor blood, rather than the presence of antibodies on which the tests used previously were based.
NAT tests allowed to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our blood techniques may reveal the first viruses, explains the specialist.
We managed to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have substantially reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing and without finding out.
These improvements allowed to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
The risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood is one out of 12 million today.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Quebec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood product.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe blood transfusions needed to heal," says the head of management of Hém-Quebek.
"The challenge for the next decades is to keep our products safe.
We never know what kind of fertilising element might appear in the system.
Just last year, a virus of chikungunya appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by an insect stab.
We need to be careful constantly," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that Héma-Québec must also count on sufficient supplies in addition to safe supply.
"The needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for a blood donor network, which consists on average of only 3% of the Québecans allowed to donate."
Each healthy person is at least 18 years old, corresponding to admissibility criteria, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people offering blood are not accepted because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud fevers occur, they are excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3% we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how they grow old and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give blood, especially to keep and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unfettered today that we will rarely find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary writes.
With an annual budget of $297 million Héma-Quebec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eye tubers and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are stored with Hém-Québek, which also manages a single public blood bank from the cord of Québek.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, flows blood rich in stem cells that can treat serious diseases, such as leukaemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand-thousand blood sample from the umbilical cord to the bank, and we assume that we will be collecting more than a thousand of them a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," says Dr. Décary, who describes the blood collection program from the cord as very popular.
"Some moms are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Quebec does not have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all the hospitals in Quebec.
