Operation to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and the heads of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest rescue economic plan since the great crisis of the 1930s.
The new version of the plan, with the help of $700 billion to slow down the financial crisis that has been clouding Wall Street for months, has yet to be approved by the two chambers of Congress.
In particular, it assumes: better control of elected representatives over its applications, new mechanisms to ensure that public money is paid, new measures to capture the number of houses confiscated for non-payment, and the right to monitor the level of wages paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
US Secretary of Finance Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and the Republicans at the table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news a few minutes after midnight, after the end of the two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective on the markets," said the Bush administration representative, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is a crucial point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and the disruption of the American daily life will be enormous," said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the last few hours, negotiations have started to peak from fear of the effect of another failure to deploy investors.
The time limit set was to open the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US president were invited to the negotiations later and both expressed their views on the agreement rather than forgetting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
The Democratic Senator Barack Obama has taken note of the addition of the agreement on certain measures, in particular the aim of which is to enable owners to maintain their residence and the wage arrangements of the state of employment of the rescued companies.
"When we ask the taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on TV waves.
His Republican opponent John McCain, who was asked by another station to vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I would love to see the details, but I hope so."
"The gross features I've read show that this is something that we're all going to have to spend and use to move on.
Selecting inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The objective of the 700 billion-dollar plan is to buy out doubtful debts and risk-free and non-sell assets from US financial institutions with the money of taxpayers.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis triggered by the collapse of the real estate bubble, which first led to the collapse of risk mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in the freeze of cash and in the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
The failure of the first draft agreement last week is a matter for Republican Members.
From the moment the Democrats agreed that for some "toxic" assets of companies having difficulties, the government will only guarantee, but it will not buy them, there is a conviction that the impenetrable situation is overrun.
In order to bring the conflicting views in Congress closer together, measures were put in place to enable the government to introduce new charges that would help it to recover its contribution if, as a result of the programme, it had to take over losses for a period of five years.
The new plan will count on the first 250 billion to which an additional 100 billion could be added if the President considers it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should approve Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in saved companies that, in the event of a profit, will pay him dividends and which he will be able to sell again when it's over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the real estate seizure procedures associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as setting limits for the amount of evaluation and compensation paid to the managers of the companies affected.
The plan's engineers would like to put it to the vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet clear whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, the vote against this project continued to be raised both in the Republican and democratic camp.
"It is clear that Washington can't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's financial committee, said to the voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money on taxpayers is not the solution."
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, moderator of a group of congressmen named "the committee of skeptics", presents the whole matter differently, but the same conclusion occurs.
"Four hundred professors of economics, among them three Nobel Prize winners, wrote: we ask Congress not to rush too quickly and carefully examine which way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis was a global crisis.
After the extraordinary meeting, three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis Group for EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion).
The intervention of the Governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitors, which has been on the verge of collapse since it lost EUR 2 billion ($2.9 billion) as a result of the crisis of risk loans to buy properties in the United States.
