The Psychology of Trucking: Why are we spending more money?
During the auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this famous - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been found by researchers in the field of neurology and economics of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in Science, people do not want to fall behind in the eBay auction, so they will pay too high a price.
Research was using an experimental auction to map the diagram of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers was betting, the other group participated in the live auction, with the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) examined the active brain area of experimental persons.
In both games, the participants could win money, but in the auction game, the important element of which is to overtrust the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to function intensively in losing.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
It is therefore possible, according to the investigators, to explain the attempt to avoid the sharp reaction of striates.
To support their theory, members of the research team of economists carried out a financial cross-sectional investigation.
Under different conditions, three groups auctioned against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the next group were promised that if they come out of the game victoriously, they would receive $15 more for the reward.
On the other hand, the third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost that money.
Thus, the difference between the two groups consisted of all things in the fact that one was highlighted by the victory and the other by the loss.
However, the members of the group who played "anti-lost" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winner" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be derived from any existing economic theory.
These have so far explained the phenomena observed in auctions with the joys of victory and avoiding risk.
Until the neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the conflict between these two theories so that we have now reached a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to find a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people around the world are suffering from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is reported among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms, there are many similarities, symptomatic of which is hepatitis and jaundice, but the cause of the disease and the disease caused by it is different from one another.
The hepatitis virus is spread in two main ways depending on the cause of the disease: hepatitis A and E digestive tracts (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood and fluid viruses (sperms, vaginal secret, saliva).
In any event, travellers should be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus type C.
Signs of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after taking an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, an urge to vomiting.
Then the skin and eye whites form jaundice, light stools and darkens urine. Treatment may take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide will die from a more serious type of disease, liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected medically treated.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected with their disease don't even know, the cause of the disease destroys liver cells viciously, and so the first symptoms occur in many cases only 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, implementation of regular depreciation is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, between drug users and between people with a tattoo.
Currently, the estimated global number of subjects infected with chronic hepatitis C is 200 million.
Since the disease can prove a routine laboratory examination, the person should contact his/her physician if he/she notices any symptoms of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent infections and prevent cancer.
September 30 is a world day for hepatitis, which was organized for the first time globally by organisations representing the sick in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by these viruses, to the causes of its origin and to the importance of early recognition of the disease.
