Smart car mimics the flight of bumblebee
What would possibly be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitating detectors of obstacles occurring in the world of nature?
For example, bees.
The initial strategic idea of a surprising project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC fair, was inspired by engineers from Nissan's company. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan constructed a bio-imimetic robotic control system such as BR23C, a robotized miniauto equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate any collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety package," explained Kazuhiro Doi, Director-General of the brand for Technology PR and Research and Development.
Complex eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see more than 300 degrees in all directions in the visual angle.
To copy the complex eye function, the engineers reached for the idea of a laser remotemeter.
This identifies obstacles up to 2 meters in front of BR23C in the field of view 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotized car starts to imitate the movements of the bee and turn the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision instantly changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver is carried out in a completely instinctive way.
"If that were not the case, a robot car could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
They must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and innermost layer of safety packaging, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid any more bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction that the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and slowdown was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium polymer accumulators that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent reactions are important, not the ability to process, but the less storage of data.
This mechanism must only process and respond to several incoming signals per second.
There is no need to store and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, therefore it uses only the memory of a few kilobytes.
He doesn't need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing technologies for immediate avoidance that, according to Nissan's estimate, could enter serial-produced cars within 10 years.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding the roadway of the obstacles, would lead the motorist to the final target set.
