The 700 billion dollar bailout package, which is to be divided into several instalments, aims to buy out poor bank loans, is already in writing.
Half the amount will be used in the first round.
Following further negotiations, which ended on Saturday after midnight in the American Eastern Time, Congress officials agreed on a daily debate on the rescue package of $700 billion in total, Reuters.
"We have made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, democratic President of the House of Representatives, according to which only the writing of the agreement remains.
Both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain also supported the package compromise.
Henry Paulson, Minister of Finance, stated on the outcome of the compromise: 'The programme will work and will be effective, but further steps must be taken'.
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. of Washington time (now on Monday at 2 p.m. of Central European Time), but no particular rise on the stock exchanges was caused.
The House of Representatives will vote first on Monday on the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilisation Act.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and then they welcomed the deal in the White House.
"We are satisfied with the progress made at night and we appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, spokesperson of the White House.
In fact, the programme differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration, in which it was intended to spend a total of $700 billion on the purchase of non-quality mortgage-backed securities.
It is now possible to spend up to half the amount of 700 billion in the first round, so that 250 billion will be used immediately after the Congress decides on the matters expected on Monday, and the Ministry of Finance will buy mortgage-backed securities, which are assessed as non-quality, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will depend on the President's decision.
The programme will be controlled by a special body, which will also be a member of the Federal Reserve Bank.
The second half of $700 billion will depend on the next Congress decision.
The Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic within the meaning of the law: it can at the same time buy out poor-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities and other "toxic" loans.
The buy-back may take place in the framework of the auctions and directly, as communicated by the competent representatives of the Ministry.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance provides them with a guarantee of funds representing a cause of concern, for which the companies will then pay a price equal to the amount of the expected damage.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary means to meet the urgent requirements of the US financial system for up to $700 billion, whether it is a large-scale purchase of bad money, their insurance, or to prevent a systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the large financial institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be prepared to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, the chiefs of banks, who are in trouble awaiting state aid, can count on the government to reduce their paychecks - which in overseas slang is simply called "a golden parachute".
The limitation of their payouts will occur only in certain cases, in addition, these restrictions will depend on the way of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The limitation basically means that if the Ministry buys in the auction, a tax premium will be imposed on the gold parachutes if the fallen bank directors are not sent straight to retirement.
In the event of direct buy-back of poor loans, the government will aggressively intervene in order to ensure that management money is not excessive.
It is necessary to add that the existing Golden Fallout Contracts will not change, the limitation only applies to new contracts, which is to be a further incentive to participate in the programme.
"This is the first time in American history that there will be legal restrictions on the remuneration of general managers," commented the President of the Committee on Financial Services of the House of Representatives, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State will retain the right to a share in the banks participating in the programme, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as once the economy and the rescued bank are on their feet, they can also earn money on the transaction.
The draft plan contains that in the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal setting out how the expected losses from the financial sector can be recovered from taxpayers.
Of course, there were also voices in relation to the plan of doubt on both sides.
"This is not what the American citizens asked for, because dollars of taxpayers won't protect," said Republican Congressman Darrell Issa of California.
His democratic colleague, Ohio Mary Kaptur, believes that it was precisely those responsible for the Wall Street collapse who insisted on the adoption of the provisions.
