Often, historical places filled with memories disappear,"it's like if we lost a friend, a friend with whom we shared a little bit of travel and a lot of emotions», the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that he won to Tornator Oscar 20 years ago and a great jury prize in Cannes, and who told the poetry of a rural cinema and sadness over a way of life that probably lost the cinema forever.
The values obtained by Anec, the main association of operators, are clear: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional tip closed doors, and the highest account has been paid mainly by halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Torina, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with a loss of 82 cinema halls followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And proof that the first responsibility for their disappearance is the onset of multiplex are these three Italian regions that have registered the highest number of new cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
«Italian progress has evolved unrationally» claims Paolo Protti, President of Anec,"it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that those already existing survive because when one cinema closes in the city, not all of its visitors are willing to move to multiplex.
Then let us not even talk about insufficient funding for the fund to the benefit of operators: the previous government debt is approximately EUR 10 million.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is shameful that the government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed».
Interesting is the Bologna case, the first Italian city to worry about closures, which decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first such type in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas in both historical centers and suburbs.
Among the planned standards are steps of tax relief for operators and benefits for the audience in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter a restricted transport zone and will have special prices to stop and some parking spaces.
«I like this initiative» says Giuseppe Tornatore and I hope that the other cities will follow the example of Bologna by introducing other measures».
However, it is certain that in order to be able to oppose the great power of multiplex, traditional halls must improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
